<div id="introduction" class="section level2">
<p>Statspeare is an R package developed for use with Dr. Michael Gavin’s “Mathematics for Shakespeare” class. It contains many of the methods and tools that students may use for assistance in performing statistical analyses on Shakespeare’s plays as well as works from the Early English Books Online database.</p>
<div id="installation" class="section level5">
<h5>Installation</h5>
<p>If you have <code>devtools</code> installed, Statspeare can be installed using <code>devtools::install_github(&quot;ajfabry/Statspeare&quot;)</code> and loaded with <code>library(Statspeare)</code>. Otherwise, you’ll need to install <code>devtools</code> first, using <code>install.packages(&quot;devtools&quot;)</code>, and load it by running <code>library(devtools)</code>.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="methods" class="section level2">
<h2>Methods</h2>
<div id="loading-data" class="section level5">
<h5>Loading Data</h5>
<p>Loading data from Statspeare can be done using the following command:</p>
<pre><code>load(system.file(&quot;extdata&quot;, &quot;W.rda&quot;, package = &quot;Statspeare&quot;))</code></pre>
<p>In this command, <code>W.rda</code> can be replaced with any of the data files within Statspeare. Data from outside Statspeare can also be loaded in the global environment for use with any Statspeare function.</p>
</div>
<div id="vector-statistics" class="section level5">
<h5>Vector Statistics</h5>
<p>Statspeare can run a number of single-vector statistic calculations, including mean, variance, standard deviation, z-score, entropy, and positive pointwise mutual information (PPMI). To calculate the z-scores of all items within a vector, for instance, one could run:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">zscore</span>(<span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>,<span class="dv">4</span>))
<span class="co">#&gt; [1] -1.3416408 -0.4472136  0.4472136  1.3416408</span></code></pre></div>
<p>An application of this could be to find out which of Shakespeare’s plays use the word “love” the most:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">sort</span>(<span class="kw">zscore</span>(P[<span class="st">&quot;love&quot;</span>,]), <span class="dt">decreasing =</span> T)
<span class="co">#&gt;         TGV         Rom         AYL         MND         Ado         LLL </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;  3.27649784  2.47088097  1.75477708  1.36688748  1.12818619  0.94916021 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;         Oth          TN          R3         Ham         Tro         Shr </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;  0.77013424  0.77013424  0.41208230  0.35240698  0.35240698  0.32256932 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;         AWW          MV          Lr         Wiv         3H6          H5 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;  0.29273166  0.26289399  0.05403036 -0.09515795 -0.27418392 -0.30402158 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;         Ant          Jn          JC         Tim          R2         Cor </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; -0.36369690 -0.36369690 -0.48304755 -0.48304755 -0.54272288 -0.66207352 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;         Cym          MM         1H4         1H6         Per          WT </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; -0.66207352 -0.66207352 -0.69191118 -0.75158651 -0.75158651 -0.78142417 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;          H8         Tit         2H4         Mac         2H6         Err </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; -0.81126183 -0.84109949 -0.87093716 -0.93061248 -0.99028780 -1.07980079 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;         Tmp </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; -1.13947611</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="vector-calculations" class="section level5">
<h5>Vector Calculations</h5>
<p>Statspeare can also handle several multi-vector calculations, including dot product, covariance, correlation, relative entropy, and cosine similarity. The correlation coefficient between two integer vectors could be determined as follows:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">correlation</span>(<span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>,<span class="dv">4</span>), <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>,<span class="dv">5</span>))
<span class="co">#&gt; [1] 0.9827076</span></code></pre></div>
<p>We can use this command to determine the correlation coefficient between two words across EEBO:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">correlation</span>(W[<span class="st">&quot;loue&quot;</span>,], W[<span class="st">&quot;hate&quot;</span>,])
<span class="co">#&gt; [1] 0.7694815</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="word-association" class="section level5">
<h5>Word Association</h5>
<p>The <code>top_relations()</code> function in Statspeare provides the user with the ability to find the list of words that are most associated with an input word. This function accepts four inputs: the matrix <code>m</code> across which word associations are calculated, the <code>word</code> to be analyzed, an optional association <code>method</code>, and an optional <code>num_results</code>. <code>top_relations</code> supports three word association methods: “most correlated,” “most similar,” and “least divergent.” If one were to find the top 15 words similar in usage to “loue” in EEBO, they could run this command:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">top_relations</span>(W, <span class="st">&quot;loue&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;most similar&quot;</span>, <span class="dv">15</span>)
<span class="co">#&gt;      loue     loues     loued    louers   delight     louer     sweet </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; 1.0000000 0.8689220 0.8639694 0.8517848 0.8297960 0.8175777 0.8155304 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;  thoughts    louely      sigh        my     ioyes      mine  sweetest </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; 0.8044113 0.8034515 0.7995116 0.7965132 0.7891932 0.7889893 0.7807938 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;     kisse </span>
<span class="co">#&gt; 0.7772702</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="centrality-measures" class="section level5">
<h5>Centrality Measures</h5>
<p>Statspeare provides the unique capability of calculating the most central characters in a play of Shakespeare’s by using the <code>centrality()</code> function. This function accepts an input of a 3-character ID <code>play</code> and a centrality measure <code>measure</code>. Statspeare currently supports three different centrality measures: “betweenness,” “degree,” and “eigenvector.” If we wanted to determine the character with the highest number of relations to others, we could run the following:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">centrality</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Ham&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;degree&quot;</span>)
<span class="co">#&gt;     Claudius       Hamlet      Laertes      Ophelia     Polonius </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;           11            9            5            5            5 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;     Gertrude Guildenstern  Rosencrantz     Barnardo    Francisco </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;            3            2            2            1            1 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;      Horatio    Marcellus        Osric     Reynaldo    Voltemand </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;            1            1            1            1            1 </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;        Ghost </span>
<span class="co">#&gt;            1</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="graphing-networks" class="section level5">
<h5>Graphing Networks</h5>
<p>Lastly, Statspeare provides the user with the ability to display the character network of relationships of any play in the corpus. Relationships in this network are determined using the <code>character_metadata.rda</code> file included in Statspeare. Plotting the network graph for a play is as simple as running this command:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">show_graph</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Rom&quot;</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="conclusion" class="section level2">
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>Statspeare can equip any aspiring data analyst of Shakespeare with the tools needed to hit the ground running with quality analysis.</p>
</div>
